<paragraph pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
According to the image in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Flora Brasiliensis</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus ottonis" order="Solanales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ottonis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Convolvulus ottonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents a plant with broadly elliptic sepals similar to the neotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus montevidensis" order="Solanales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="montevidensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Convolvulus montevidensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The neotype may or may not represent part of the original collection on which 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sprengel’s">Sprengel's</normalizedToken>
description was based but was collected by Sellow at Montevideo and originates from the Berlin herbarium. It shows the large corolla and reddish brown sepals so characteristic of this subspecies which is common in parts of Paraguay, southern Brazil, northern Argentina and Uruguay.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
There is at least one collection from Paraguay (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Hansen</emphasis>
7679 [C, NY]) which shows evidence of introgression with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O'Donell, Lilloa 23: 430. 1950. (O'Donell" authorityYear="1950" baseAuthorityName="Chodat" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus hasslerianus" order="Solanales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hasslerianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Convolvulus hasslerianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The calyx is that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus crenatifolius subsp. montevidensis" order="Solanales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="crenatifolius" subSpecies="montevidensis">Convolvulus crenatifolius subsp. montevidensis</taxonomicName>
but the flowers are solitary and the leaves are very shortly petiolate with subentire margins.
</paragraph>
